-- Most Asian Stocks Fall; Fast Retailing Drops, Samsung Gains
-- Lisa Pham
-- 2010-07-09T02:51:03Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-07-09/most-asian-stocks-fall-fast-retailing-drops-samsung-gains.html

          
          
             Asian  stocks  rose after South Korea
raised its benchmark interest rate for the first time since the
global financial crisis and after a report  Canon Inc. ’s profit
may almost have tripled.  
 KB Financial Group Inc.  climbed 3.6 percent in Seoul,
leading South Korean banks higher. Woori Finance Holdings Co.
climbed 3.8 percent.  Canon Inc.  jumped 1.2 percent after Nikkei
English News reported the camera maker’s group operating profit
the first half may have almost tripled. Samsung Electronics Co.,
which gets a fifth of its revenue in America, gained 0.3 percent
after U.S. jobless claims fell.  Fast Retailing Ltd. , Asia’s
biggest clothing retailer, sank 1.2 percent in Tokyo after
cutting its full-year net income target.  
 “The U.S. jobless data shows the economy is slowly
recovering,” said  Yoji Takeda , who manages about $1.1 billion
at RBC Investment (Asia) Ltd. in Hong Kong.  
 About the same number of stocks rose as fell among the 985
companies in the  MSCI Asia Pacific Index , which climbed 0.4
percent to 115.52 as of 11:49 a.m. in Tokyo. The gauge surged
1.6 percent yesterday after the International Monetary Fund
raised its global economic growth forecast. It has slumped 11
percent from its high this year on April 15 on concern Europe’s
debt crisis and Chinese steps to curb property prices will hurt
global growth.  
